_**Crank Yankers**_ is an American [television show](/wiki/Television_show
"Television show") produced by [Adam Carolla](/wiki/Adam_Carolla "Adam
Carolla"), [Jimmy Kimmel](/wiki/Jimmy_Kimmel "Jimmy Kimmel") and [Daniel
Kellison](/wiki/Daniel_Kellison "Daniel Kellison") that featured actual [crank
calls](/wiki/Crank_call "Crank call") made by show regulars and celebrity
guests, and re-enacted onscreen by [puppets](/wiki/Puppet "Puppet") for a
visual aid to show the viewer what is happening in the call. The show
premiered in 2002 on [Comedy Central](/wiki/Comedy_Central "Comedy Central")
and returned to [MTV2](/wiki/MTV2 "MTV2") on February 9, 2007, running again
until March 30, 2007. The show screened in Australia on [SBS
Television](/wiki/SBS_Television "SBS Television") and [The Comedy
Channel](/wiki/The_Comedy_Channel "The Comedy Channel") between 2003 and
2008.[_[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation
needed")_]

## Behind the
scenes[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Crank_Yankers&action=edit&section=1 "Edit
section: Behind the scenes")]

The performers are given a basic outline of a premise by the writers, and call
telephone numbers from a list of selected targets (known as "marks"). Using
the basic premises, the performers improvise most of their lines, playing off
of the responses of their marks, with the intention to keep them on the phone
as long as possible.

With the exception of a few outside sources (including previous material from
Jim Florentine and the [Touch-Tone Terrorists](/wiki/Touch-Tone_Terrorists
"Touch-Tone Terrorists")), all the calls are made from [Nevada](/wiki/Nevada
"Nevada"). The [Omnibus Crime Control and Safe Streets Act of
1968](/wiki/Omnibus_Crime_Control_and_Safe_Streets_Act_of_1968 "Omnibus Crime
Control and Safe Streets Act of 1968") makes it illegal in most states to
record telephone calls without both parties' consent. Under Nevada law, only
one of the parties has to give consent (i.e., the caller), so prank calls can
be recorded without the consent of the prank victims. One result of this was
the series' schedule of creating and airing new episodes was fairly sporadic
due to most of the celebrities living in Los Angeles, having Los Angeles-based
jobs, and so were only periodically able to go to Las Vegas to make calls.
Adam Carolla, for example, took [his radio
program](/wiki/The_Adam_Carolla_Show_\(terrestrial_radio\) "The Adam Carolla
Show \(terrestrial radio\)") to Las Vegas once or twice a year, and while
there would record new calls for the program.

The puppets are then constructed based on the various marks' voices, and,
along with a series of stock characters (such as "Niles Standish", "Bobby
Fletcher", and "Special Ed") based on the performers' character voices, the
calls are re-enacted for the skits.

The main character puppets for the first season were constructed by Bob
Flanagan's company [Den
Design](/w/index.php?title=Den_Design&action=edit&redlink=1 "Den Design \(page
does not exist\)") with additional puppets built by BJ Guyer, Carol Binion,
Rick Lyon, Ron Binion, Jim Kroupa, and Artie Esposito. An in-house puppet shop
was set up for the following seasons to accommodate the fast-paced schedule of
the show and the sheer volume of puppet characters required for each episode.

The puppets are puppeteered by Ronald Binion, Rick Lyon, BJ Guyer, Victor
Yerrid, Paul McGinnis, Alice Dinean Vernon, and Artie Esposito.[_[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_]

Originally, the show was titled _Prank Puppets_ ; it was renamed after Comedy
Central lawyers deemed that it implied [malice](/wiki/Malice_\(law\) "Malice
\(law\)").[2]

## Regular
characters[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Crank_Yankers&action=edit&section=2 "Edit
section: Regular characters")]

  * **Karl Malone** : Jimmy Kimmel's impression of then-[NBA](/wiki/NBA "NBA") star [Karl Malone](/wiki/Karl_Malone "Karl Malone"). He regularly refers to himself in the third-person. "Don't hang up on Karl Malone."
  * **Gladys Murphy** ([Wanda Sykes](/wiki/Wanda_Sykes "Wanda Sykes")): A boisterous black woman who makes embarrassing announcements, generally of a [scatological](/wiki/Scatology "Scatology") or sexual nature. Her many children do things like gluing her buttocks to the toilet and stealing money from a malfunctioning bank machine.
  * **Niles Standish** ([Tony Barbieri](/wiki/Anthony_Barbieri "Anthony Barbieri")): The British Earl of Yankerville, he is a rich and eccentric middle-aged pervert with [homosexual](/wiki/Homosexual "Homosexual") tendencies. He frequently calls various services and asks for their price, then orders them to "double it." (Once even confusing someone by telling them to "cut it in half, and double it!").
  * **Special Ed** ([Jim Florentine](/wiki/Jim_Florentine "Jim Florentine")): Bobby Fletcher's mentally challenged younger cousin who constantly repeats himself, makes random comments, and shouts his catchphrase "Yay!" until the other caller gets frustrated. He makes a cameo in one of Bobby's prank calls, the "Let Me Put My Brother on the Phone" call. In two prank calls of his own (one to a [movie theater](/wiki/Movie_theater "Movie theater") and one to a [video store](/wiki/Video_store "Video store")), Ed reveals that his favorite movie is _[Air Bud](/wiki/Air_Bud "Air Bud")_. In the video-store call, he works in several references to _[The Shining](/wiki/The_Shining_\(film\) "The Shining \(film\)")_.
  * **Dick Birchum** ([Adam Carolla](/wiki/Adam_Carolla "Adam Carolla")): A psychotic [Vietnam War](/wiki/Vietnam_War "Vietnam War") veteran whose hobbies include [carpentry](/wiki/Carpentry "Carpentry"), [Shotokan karate](/wiki/Shotokan "Shotokan"), spying on women in their beds or bathrooms by drilling holes or a hidden camera, and gun ownership. He has a 600-pound wife and conjoined twin daughters. He lost part of his right leg in the war and 3 right-hand fingers in a carpentry accident. He frequently refers to his time in Vietnam and "smoking hash out of a human skull."
  * **Jimmy** ([Jimmy Kimmel](/wiki/Jimmy_Kimmel "Jimmy Kimmel")): A Kimmel-based grown man who lives with his mother. He also has 2 young children who use foul language and play juvenile pranks.
  * **Bobby Fletcher** ([Jim Florentine](/wiki/Jim_Florentine "Jim Florentine")): Ed's drug-using underachiever older cousin. He is extremely rude and insulting, and known for generating copious amounts of gas and [belching](/wiki/Belch "Belch") into the phone.
  * **Elmer Higgins** ([Jimmy Kimmel](/wiki/Jimmy_Kimmel "Jimmy Kimmel")): A crabby, long-winded stereotype of an elderly man (based on Kimmel's grandfather). He makes complaint calls and frequently goes off on unrelated, long-winded tangents about his younger days and various irrelevant subjects. He frequently blames the situations he's complaining about on his [gay](/wiki/Homosexuality "Homosexuality") grandson, Terrance Catheter.
  * **Helen Higgins** ([Susie Essman](/wiki/Susie_Essman "Susie Essman")): Elmer's beautiful wife of over 60 years, she is an elderly Jewish woman who likes to proposition young men. Her son gave her a pet parrot who is well-versed in curse words. In a late-in-the-series sketch about Elmer wanting driving lessons, he mentions that she has died.
  * **Landalious "The Truth" Truefeld** ([David Alan Grier](/wiki/David_Alan_Grier "David Alan Grier")): A former football player who likes to rap.
  * **Spoonie Luv** ([Tracy Morgan](/wiki/Tracy_Morgan "Tracy Morgan")): A smooth-talking African American [hip hop](/wiki/Hip_hop_culture "Hip hop culture")-type character who makes lewd and suggestive comments. He often refers to himself as "Spoonie Luv from Up Above." In one particularly noteworthy prank call, he attempts to sell a video store tapes of himself [masturbating](/wiki/Masturbation "Masturbation").
  * **Hadassah Guberman** ([Sarah Silverman](/wiki/Sarah_Silverman "Sarah Silverman")): A Jewish female college student who works various part-time jobs, including conducting surveys for _[O](/wiki/O,_The_Oprah_Magazine "O, The Oprah Magazine")_ magazine. She frequently asks intrusive questions and makes veiled [passive-aggressive](/wiki/Passive-aggressive_behavior "Passive-aggressive behavior") insults. Her sexuality and sanity seem highly questionable.
  * **Terrence Catheter** ([Jimmy Kimmel](/wiki/Jimmy_Kimmel "Jimmy Kimmel")): Elmer Higgins' grandson is an effeminate redhead who acts as spokesperson for various celebrities, such as [Tom Cruise](/wiki/Tom_Cruise "Tom Cruise"), [Bill Cosby](/wiki/Bill_Cosby "Bill Cosby"), [Jared Fogle](/wiki/Jared_Fogle "Jared Fogle"), [J.K. Rowling](/wiki/J.K._Rowling "J.K. Rowling"), [Mr. T](/wiki/Mr._T "Mr. T"), and the [Olsen twins](/wiki/Mary-Kate_and_Ashley_Olsen "Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen"). He calls various places of business to book appearances and asks them to comply with the celebrities' ridiculous demands.
  * **Tony Deloge** ([Bob Einstein](/wiki/Bob_Einstein "Bob Einstein")): A loud-mouthed, fast-paced politician who calls random people to pander for votes as "district selectman." He occasionally tries to use his political power to get things for free.
  * **Cammie Smith** ([Lisa Kushell](/wiki/Lisa_Kushell "Lisa Kushell")): An oversexed, conceited, condescending 22-year-old exotic dancer.
  * **Boomer and the Nudge** ([Jimmy Kimmel](/wiki/Jimmy_Kimmel "Jimmy Kimmel") and [Patton Oswalt](/wiki/Patton_Oswalt "Patton Oswalt")): Two obnoxious morning-radio [disc jockeys](/wiki/Disc_jockey "Disc jockey") who call people to make "on-air dares."
  * **Junkyard Willie** ([Touch-Tone Terrorists](/wiki/Touch-Tone_Terrorists "Touch-Tone Terrorists")): An obstructionist in the form of a gravelly-voiced black man who is actually an import from the Touch-Tone Terrorists where he is a regular character. He appears in two sketches as a supervisor at YPS ("Yankerville Package Service").
  * **Jim Bob the Handicapped Hillbilly** ([Touch-Tone Terrorists](/wiki/Touch-Tone_Terrorists "Touch-Tone Terrorists")): A mentally challenged hillbilly who works with Junkyard Willie at YPS.
  * **Sav Macauley** ([Dane Cook](/wiki/Dane_Cook "Dane Cook")): The overly enthusiastic host of a phone [game show](/wiki/Game_show "Game show"), "The Phone Zone," where he calls people and asks ridiculous random trivia questions for cash prizes and interjects his own sound effects.
  * **OCD Ken** ([Kevin Nealon](/wiki/Kevin_Nealon "Kevin Nealon")): An accountant with [obsessive-compulsive disorder](/wiki/Obsessive-compulsive_disorder "Obsessive-compulsive disorder") who prefers cleanliness and [even](/wiki/Even_and_odd_numbers "Even and odd numbers") numbers. He often requests people to press the [pound](/wiki/Number_sign "Number sign") key as part of his disorder.
  * **Danny** ([David Alan Grier](/wiki/David_Alan_Grier "David Alan Grier")): A man who repeatedly gets nervous or disgusted causing him to vomit over the phone. The vomit is depicted as an _[Exorcist](/wiki/Exorcist "Exorcist")_ -like liquid shooting out of the puppet's throat.
  * **Chip Douglas** ([Fred Armisen](/wiki/Fred_Armisen "Fred Armisen")): A [Mexican](/wiki/Mexico "Mexico") immigrant who is perpetually building a house with minimal supplies and poor command of the English language. He makes two prank calls to [newspaper](/wiki/Newspaper "Newspaper") offices, one to attempt to sell cartoons and the other (a prank call in [Spanish](/wiki/Spanish_language "Spanish language")) to inform a Spanish-language newspaper that he has not received that day's edition.
  * **Katie** (Katie Kimmel): Jimmy Kimmel's daughter made occasional appearances from 2003, initially with a few short lines but later making entire crank calls herself (notably pretending to be a drunken 9-year-old trying to order alcohol by phone).
  * **Kevin** (Kevin Kimmel): Jimmy Kimmel's son made occasional appearances from 2003, including as Elmer Higgins' grandson.
  * **Foreign Guy** ([Dane Cook](/wiki/Dane_Cook "Dane Cook")): A nameless immigrant who calls various places looking for assistance or to purchase something. To confuse the person he calls, he frequently switches between speaking in extremely broken English in an incomprehensible accent to speaking fluently, with no accent. The switch is demonstrated visually by having the puppet move between the two halves of a room across a clear dividing line.
  * **Gene Winterbuck** ([Dane Cook](/wiki/Dane_Cook "Dane Cook")): A wheelchair-bound young man who calls libraries requesting books with titles referring to disabilities, such as "Johnny NoodleLegs".
  * **Lou Vilman** ([Kevin Nealon](/wiki/Kevin_Nealon "Kevin Nealon")): An easily impressed guy who responds "Wow!" to everything.
  * **Dick Rogers** ([Seth MacFarlane](/wiki/Seth_MacFarlane "Seth MacFarlane")): A stereotypical fast-talking 1940s detective whose sketches appear in black-and-white. He'll often call to complain about issues that would make someone from the 1940s uncomfortable, such as being hit on by men at a [gay bar](/wiki/Gay_bar "Gay bar") or getting a haircut from a female hairdresser. He also calls the [YMCA](/wiki/YMCA "YMCA") for help with his alcohol problem.[_[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_]
